The genus 

Euphorbia

has attracted a great attention in the search for natural-product-based drugs as an abundant source of bioactive terpenoids (

; 

; 

; 

; 

; Zhao et al., 2018). With over 2000 known species is the largest genus in the plant family 

Euphorbiaceae (
Jassbi, 2006
)

, and no less than 400 diterpenoids isolated from plants of that genus exhibit relevant biological activities (

; 

; 

; 

). Many plants species of the 
Euphorbiaceae
family produce diterpenoids with jatrophane, lathyrane, tigliane, daphnane, ingenane, or myrsinane skeleta which show a broad range of interesting pharmacological properties such as antitumor and multidrug resistance reversing activities (

, 

; 

; 

; 

; Wang et al., 2015; Zhang et al., 2019). The ability of members of these classes of compounds to modulate protein kinase C (PKCs) (Dur´an-Pe˜na et al., 2014) is associated with a wide variety of biological activities such as cell differentiation (Weinstein et al., 1979; 

), skin inflammation (

), tumor promotion (

; 

), cytotoxicity (

), latent HIV-1 reactivation (

; 

; 

; Marquez´et al., 2008; 

), and recently in neural precursor proliferation (Castro-Gonz´alez et al., 2013, 2015; 

; Flores-Giubi et al., 2019).

Among 
Euphorbiaceae
family diterpenes, jatrophane diterpenoids are ubiquitous metabolites of genera 

Euphorbia

and 

Jatropha
(
Sabandar et al., 2013
)

. The general structure of the jatrophane skeleton is characterized by a 5/12 fused-ring system and they are usually substituted by a variety of acyl groups to 

form polyesters (
Fattahian et al., 2020
)

. Interestingly, it has been described that some jatrophane diterpenoids have anti-cancer activity (

; 

), as well as microtubule interacting activity (

) and act 
in vitro
against HIV-1 (

) and CHIKV viruses (

; 

); furthermore, they are considered among the most potent modulators of P-glycoproteins that reverse multidrug resistance (

; 

; 

; 

; 

).

The HMBC cross-peaks from H-8 ( δ H 5.34 ppm) and H-14 ( δ H 4.79 ppm) to δ C 169.2 and 170.4 ppm, respectively, indicated two acetoxy groups attached to C-8 and C-14 whereas the benzoate chain was located at C-9 due to HMBC cross-peaks from H-9 ( δ H 4.60 ppm) to carbonyl carbon of the benzoyl group at δ C 167.4 ppm. The remaining acetoxy group could not be directly attached by HMBC experiments due to the lack of direct correlations. The comparison of the chemical shifts and coupling constants of H-3 and H-2 with those observed in the literature for other related jatrophanes pointed out that it must be located at C-3 (
,
;
;
;
). Finally, the free hydroxyl groups were deduced to be attached to C-7 and C-15. The gCOSY correlations observed for protons H-7 ( δ H 4.16 ppm) and OH-7 ( δ H 4.85 ppm) indicated the presence of a hydroxyl group at C-7. The remaining one hydroxyl group must be located at C-15 due to the shielding of that nucleus in the 13 C NMR spectrum in comparison to other related-jatrophanes (Table S9) ( Fig. 2 ) (
,
;
;
;
). A new signal at δ H 7.27 ppm in the 1 H NMR spectrum in C 6 D 6 , which partially exchanged with D 2 O, confirmed the hydroxyl group at C-15 (Table S8 and Fig. S14).

The relative configuration of 3 was deduced by the interpretation of the NOESY spectrum. The correlations of H-4/H 3 -17/H-7/H-8 and H-4/ H-13/H-11 indicated α- orientations for those protons, whereas the correlations of H-5/H-9 were used to place these protons on the opposite face of the macrocycle. The NOESY correlations of H-11/H 3 -17/H-13 and the coupling constant of J 11,12 = 15.5 Hz revealed the E -geometry of the C-11/C-12 double bond, while the E stereochemistry of the C-5/C-6 olefin linkage was deduced from NOESY correlations between H-4/H 3 - 17 and H-5/H-9. Further NOESY correlations of H 3 -16/H-3/H-4 and H-12/H 3 -20/H-14 revealed their proximity in space ( Fig. 3 ). Moreover, the coupling constant J 14,13 = 10.3 Hz ( Table 1 ) was compatible with an anti-disposition of H-13 and H-14 and it was in agreement with the values described in literature for other related-jatrophanes (
;
).

On the basis of the α- assumed configuration of H-4 and β -orientation of 15-OH, characteristic of all jatrophane-type diterpene derivatives isolated to date (
;
), and NOESY correlations the absolute configuration for 3 was suggested to be assigned as 2 R ,3 S ,4 S ,7 S ,8 S ,9 S ,13 S ,14 R ,15 R . This absolute configuration of 3 was supported by comparison of the experimental ECD spectrum with the computed ECD spectrum calculated from quantum mechanical time-dependent density functional theory (TDDFT) calculations with B3LYP/6-31G++ (d,p) level of theory, using the Gaussian 16 program (
). The theoretically calculated ECD spectrum of 3 was in good agreement with the experimental ECD spectrum ( Fig. 4 ).

In a cycloaddition reaction there is an electron density transfer from the nucleophilic to the electrophilic species (

; 

). In order to translate this concept into a computational analysis, a recent methodology has been used for obtaining bond reactivity indices (Δ 
f
i
NBO

) (S´anchez-M´arquez, 2016; 2018; 

) and philicities for every Natural Bond Orbital (NBO). These bond reactivity indices are obtained through projection of the function dual descriptor on the localized orbitals obtained in the NBO analysis allowing the reaction site of an electrophile or nucleophile to be determined within a much-localized molecular region. A negative small value of Δ 
f
i
NBO

together with a high partial occupancy indicates a nucleophilic behaviour whereas a positive value of Δ 
f
i
NBO

and a small partial occupancy corresponds to an electrophilic behaviour. For instance, this approach has been successfully applied to study previously the regioselectivity in Diels-Alder reactions (

). In addition, in this study, a Second-Order Perturbational Theory Analysis (SOPTA) (

) has been also used to complement and corroborate the results. To the best of our knowledge, these quantum methodologies have not been previously applied in clarifying biosynthetic pathways of terpenes.

The bond reactivity indices study suggests that the intramolecular [2 + 2] cycloaddition leading to gaditanone (
2
) proceeds through a photochemical non-concerted mechanism of the enone 
6
. The stereoselectivity of the cycloaddition could be understood by the delocalization of electron density over specific NBOs presumably originated from the steric effects of the substituents in the transition state avoiding the 
cis
/ 
trans
isomerization (

). Furthermore, the formation of a cyclohexanone moiety in the 5/6/4/6-fused tetracyclic ring skeleton both in gaditanone (
2
) (

) and heliosterpenoids A and B (

) seems to play a structural stabilization role, favouring the cyclization of the jatrophane precursors.

